# Rate-card history

Situational knowledge for tasks involving the rate card. Keeps always-loaded context small.

## Why surge comes before the discount

In 2023 finance asked for a flat 8 percent volume discount as a goodwill gesture for large
productions booking big crews. It was layered on top of the existing surge multiplier with
no spec. The order (surge, then discount) was an implementation accident that later became
the number printed on invoices. Changing the order changes what productions were billed
historically, so treat it as a contract, not a preference.

## The floor rate for unknown stages

`baseRate` returns 119 for any stage it does not recognize. This was a defensive default so
a typo in the stage name would not crash the quote. It also means a misspelled stage
silently books at the floor rate. A real fix validates the stage up front; do not just
change the default in passing.

## Peak definition drift

"Peak" currently means weekends plus all of July and December. Production has asked twice to
make peak data-driven (actual stage demand) rather than calendar-based. That is a real
feature, not a one-line change. If a task heads that way, write a spec first (see `specs/`).